\noindent \textbf{Abstract}\\
\textbf{1.} Hidden Markov models (HMMs) based on polar coordinates (i.e., step lengths and turn angles) have become very popular for inferring animal movement behavior states (e.g., ``foraging'', ``transit'') from biotelemetry data. HMMs using these metrics to characterize correlated random walks are attractive because they are relatively easy to implement and interpret. However, such ``step and turn'' HMMs tend to suffer from three key drawbacks: 1) they unrealistically assume that steps and turns are independent (conditional on the current state); 2) they are typically blind to the spatial mechanisms that give rise to certain movement behaviors (e.g., resource selection); and 3) they are not particularly amenable to temporally-irregular (i.e., continuous-time) observations.\\
\textbf{2.} We investigate these drawbacks using simulation, where data were generated from multi-state bivariate normal random walks in the Cartesian plane. We show that steps and turns calculated from correlated random walks on the Cartesian plane are not conditionally independent, and HMMs using these metrics can perform poorly unless the corresponding state-dependent observation distributions in the polar plane share virtually no support. This trend was exacerbated in more realistic simulations where movements followed environmental gradients (e.g., prey fields, habitat type, ocean currents)% in the Cartesian plane
, but performance was somewhat improved in spatially-explicit step and turn HMMs that included these environmental gradients in both observation distributions.\\
\textbf{3.} Unless animals are indeed making complex movement decisions in the (independent) polar plane in response to their internal and external environment, our results suggest that alternatives should be considered instead of simply defaulting to standard step and turn HMMs. As a potentially more robust alternative, we encourage formulating movement HMMs on the Cartesian coordinates directly as a multi-state bivariate (or trivariate) normal random walk. %This is demonstrated in two case studies using 2D elephant seal data and 3D harbor porpoise data. 
We demonstrate this in a case study using southern elephant seal location data. In addition to allowing for state-dependent correlation in the steps and turns, position- or velocity-based movement HMMs are much more amenable to including spatial mechanisms that are driving movements (e.g., via gradient-based potential functions) and continuous-time formulations than their polar-based counterparts. Our findings could also have implications for other movement models that utilize polar coordinates, such as step selection functions that link movement and habitat selection.\\
\textbf{4.} To aid practitioners in determining whether or not steps and turns are indeed conditionally independent, we develop a correlated HMM that is directly comparable to conventional step and turn HMMs using standard model diagnostics and/or information-theoretic approaches.  All HMMs considered here can be simulated and fitted by maximum likelihood methods using existing software. We hope this provides a potential workflow for practitioners to first assess competing movement metrics and then choose the most appropriate HMM formulation for their system and behaviors of interest.\\
\noindent \textbf{Keywords: animal biotelemetry, correlated random walk, latent Markov model, movement ecology, polar coordinates, state-switching, tracking data} 

