\section{Discussion}
Using simulation and a case study, we have demonstrated how polar-based ``step and turn'' movement HMMs that ignore correlation between step lengths and turn angles can yield inferences that significantly differ from those of position-based (Cartesian) movement HMMs. Ignoring this correlation is of little consequence when the state-dependent observation distributions share little to no support, but one of the most appealing features of a (properly specified) HMM is its ability to distinguish states when the underlying distributions are less obvious. Although standard ``step and turn'' HMMs are currently much more widely used, our results suggest practitioners should consider alternatives and not simply default to this approach. This becomes even more important as these models are increasingly being used to inform conservation and management decisions.

Despite standard step and turn models becoming commonplace over the past two decades, this issue has received remarkably little attention in the literature \citep[but see][]{hodel2022circular}. We hope our work will help bring this issue further to the forefront and provide a potential workflow to help identify which HMM formulation might be most appropriate for particular systems and behaviors of interest. We recommend that practitioners first examine their data for any correlation between step lengths and turn angles during exploratory data analysis. This can be as simple as calculating Pearson's correlation coefficient, $\corr \left(l,\left|a \right| \right)$, or visual examination of circular box plots (e.g., Fig.\ \ref{fig:sesStepTurnCor}). Correlation between step lengths and turn angles is not necessarily problematic as this can simply be induced by different movement behaviors (e.g. ``encamped'' versus ``exploratory'' movements). However, state-dependent correlation can be problematic and difficult to diagnose because the underlying states are unknown. To help identify if there may be correlation between steps and turns within a given state, one can compare the standard step and turn HMM to the correlated step and turn HMM using information criteria (e.g. AIC, BIC), pseudo-residual plots, and/or state-dependent circular box plots (as demonstrated in the southern elephant seal example). If the steps and turns are conditionally independent within each state, then the correlated step and turn HMM should not be supported by these diagnostics, thereby indicating the standard step and turn HMM sufficiently explains any correlation by simply conditioning on the latent states. The standard step and turn HMM could also be compared with the (more flexible) circular-linear copula approach of \citet{hodel2022circular}, but metrics other than information criteria and pseudo-residuals would need to be used. If evidence is found for correlation between steps and turns within a given state, our results suggest that the correlated step and turn HMM or a position-based HMM should be considered for inference. We again note that all of these steps can be performed with existing software \citep[e.g.][]{McClintockMichelot2018,hodel2022circular}.

%Beyond accounting for correlation between steps and turns, 
Beyond capitalizing on the correlations between steps and turns to help identify latent behavioral states, 
position- or velocity-based formulations pose other advantages. As demonstrated in our simulations and case study, potential functions are a much more straightforward approach to modeling more realistic movements driven by environmental gradients. It is also much easier to formulate them using time-scale invariant parameterizations or in continuous time. The primary disadvantage of modeling animal movement as a multistate bivariate (or trivariate) normal random walk is that the interpretation of the model parameters is perhaps somewhat less intuitive than in standard step and turn HMMs. However, histograms and densities of the realized state-dependent step lengths and turn angles can still be visualized (e.g., Fig.\ \ref{fig:bcrwdens}), which we find can be helpful when interpreting the output from a position-based HMM.

Perhaps most importantly, do we as movement ecologists believe steps and turns are ever actually independent? Are animals really separately choosing the speed and the direction of movement in the independent polar plane as they respond to their internal and external environment? Even within a particular movement behavior state this seems unlikely. Given the dangers associated with ignoring this correlation, we hope our work will ultimately lead to broader adoption of position-based animal movement HMMs. Our work also has implications for other analysis methods that typically assume independence between step lengths and turn angles, such as step selection functions for inferring habitat selection \citep[e.g.][]{thurfjell2014applications}. This remains a promising avenue for future research.

